<subSubSection lastPageId="66" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,1409,2012]" lastBlockId="66.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="66" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1733,1759]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[327,612,1733,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viriditibialis">
<emphasis box="[327,612,1733,1759]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Onycholyda viriditibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[866,930,1734,1760]" name="Japan" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." box="[949,1125,1733,1759]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="3 - 16" refId="ref80368" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1930) A revisional list of the Japanese Pamphiliidae, with description of nine new species. Transactions of the Kansai Entomological Society, 1, 3 - 16." type="journal article" year="1930">Takeuchi 1930</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[1149,1362,1733,1759]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="271 - 281" refId="ref76182" refString="Shinohara, A. (1986 a) The sawfly genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) of Japan III. Kontyu, Tokyo, 54, 271 - 281." type="journal article" year="1986">Shinohara (1986a)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName authority="Gussakovskij, 1935" authorityName="Gussakovskij" authorityYear="1935" box="[256,719,1769,1796]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tsherskii">
<emphasis box="[256,486,1769,1795]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Pamphilius tsherskii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gussakovskij, V. V." box="[494,719,1769,1796]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="1 - 453" refId="ref73348" refString="Gussakovskij, V. V. (1935) Insectes Hymenopteres, Chalastogastra 1. In: Fauna SSSR. 2 (1). Moskva, Leningrad, pp. 1 - 453. [in Russian and German]" type="book chapter" year="1935">Gussakovskij, 1935</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, described from Vladivostok, with this species, even though he noted a few very small colour pattern differences between them. In both COI and NaK trees (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1322,1805,1831]" captionStart="FIGURE 138" captionStartId="227.[151,250,1515,1539]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,187,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-19@227.[151,1436,181,1491]" captionTargetPageId="227" captionText="FIGURE 138. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876837/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Figs 138</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1335,1380,1805,1832]" captionStart="FIGURE 153" captionStartId="240.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@240.[172,1415,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="240" captionText="FIGURE 153. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876872/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">153</figureCitation>
), the Russian and Japanese specimens formed separate clades, each with 100% UFBoot support. The Russian and Japanese clades together formed a clade with 100% UFBoot support in the COI tree (
<figureCitation box="[1064,1160,1877,1903]" captionStart="FIGURE 138" captionStartId="227.[151,250,1515,1539]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,187,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-19@227.[151,1436,181,1491]" captionTargetPageId="227" captionText="FIGURE 138. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda, part 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876837/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
) but they did not form a clade in the NaK tree (
<figureCitation box="[409,508,1913,1940]" captionStart="FIGURE 153" captionStartId="240.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1407,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@240.[172,1415,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="240" captionText="FIGURE 153. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Onycholyda." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876872/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 153</figureCitation>
). The maximum 
<emphasis box="[700,714,1914,1939]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">p</emphasis>
-distance among the Russian specimens was 0.2% in COI (n=3) and 0% in NaK (n=2) and that among the Japanese specimens (n=4) was 0.9% in COI and 0% in NaK, whereas the minimum 
<emphasis box="[269,283,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">p</emphasis>
-distance between the two populations was 1.2% in COI and 0.4% in NaK. Apparently, there is some diversification among the geographically isolated populations, but here we treat all as a single species because we do not consider the observed differences sufficient to assume different species. The nearest neighbour was 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shinohara" authorityYear="1985" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">O. armata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in COI analysis, diverging by a minimum of 2.6%, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Benes" authorityYear="1972" box="[831,943,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sertata">
<emphasis box="[831,943,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">O. sertata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kim" authorityYear="1970" box="[996,1097,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis box="[996,1097,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">O. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in NaK analysis, diverging by a minimum of 0.5%.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
The flight period of this species is long, from May to September, in 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1098,295,321]" name="South Korea" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">South Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Tripotin, P." box="[1113,1432,295,321]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="59 - 64" refId="ref78917" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Tripotin, P. (2021 a) Some collection records of pamphiliid sawflies (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) from Korea. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 27, 59 - 64." type="journal article" year="2021">Shinohara &amp; Tripotin 2021a</bibRefCitation>
, b) and also in 
<collectingCountry box="[308,372,331,357]" name="Japan" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A." box="[386,580,331,357]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="271 - 281" refId="ref76182" refString="Shinohara, A. (1986 a) The sawfly genus Onycholyda (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) of Japan III. Kontyu, Tokyo, 54, 271 - 281." type="journal article" year="1986">Shinohara 1986a</bibRefCitation>
). The long flight period of adults is quite unusual for a pamphiliid, otherwise known only for the closely related 
<taxonomicName authority="(Takeuchi, 1938)" baseAuthorityName="Takeuchi" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[541,841,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Onycholyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esakii">
<emphasis box="[541,640,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">O. esakii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." box="[654,832,367,393]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="173 - 229" refId="ref80448" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1938) A systematic study on the suborder Symphyta (Hymenoptera) of the Japanese Empire (1). Tenthredo, 2, 173 - 229." type="journal article" year="1938">Takeuchi, 1938</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It is probably a result of polymodal adult emergence (
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kojima, H." box="[159,462,403,429]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="407 - 410" refId="ref78306" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Kojima, H. (2009) Discovery of host plant and larva of Pamphilius hortorum (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) in Honshu, Japan. Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 15, 407 - 410." type="journal article" year="2009">Shinohara &amp; Kojima 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
